URL MODULE IN NODE.JS

The url module provides utilities for URL resolution and parsing. It splits a URL into its readable parts.

Require: const url = require('url');

Main method: url.parse(urlString, parseQueryString)
- urlString: The URL to parse
- parseQueryString: true = parse query as object, false = keep as string

Parsed URL Object Properties:
- href: Full URL
- protocol: 'http:'
- host: 'localhost:8080'
- hostname: 'localhost'
- port: '8080'
- pathname: '/default.html'
- search: '?year=2023&month=june'
- query: { year: '2023', month: 'june' } (when parseQueryString=true)
- hash: '#section'

Example:
const url = require('url');
const addr = 'http://localhost:8080/results.html?year=2023&month=june#top';
const q = url.parse(addr, true);

console.log('Protocol:', q.protocol);   // http:
console.log('Hostname:', q.hostname);   // localhost
console.log('Port:', q.port);           // 8080
console.log('Pathname:', q.pathname);   // /results.html
console.log('Search:', q.search);       // ?year=2023&month=june
console.log('Query:', q.query);         // { year: '2023', month: 'june' }
console.log('Query year:', q.query.year); // 2023
console.log('Hash:', q.hash);           // #top

Use in HTTP Server:
const http = require('http');
const url = require('url');
http.createServer((req, res) => {
  const q = url.parse(req.url, true);
  const name = q.query.name || 'Guest';
  res.end('Hello, ' + name);
}).listen(3000);

JSON PROCESSING IN NODE.JS

JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) processing involves:
1. JSON.stringify() - Convert JS object to JSON string
2. JSON.parse() - Convert JSON string to JS object

