MIDDLEWARE IN EXPRESS.JS

Middleware functions have access to req, res, and next objects and execute during the request-response cycle.

Types of Middleware:
1. Application-level: app.use() or app.get()
2. Router-level: router.use()
3. Error-handling: function(err, req, res, next)
4. Built-in: express.json(), express.static()
5. Third-party: morgan, cors, body-parser

Creating Custom Middleware:

const express = require('express');
const app = express();

// Custom middleware function
const logger = (req, res, next) => {
  console.log(`[${new Date().toISOString()}] ${req.method} ${req.url}`);
  next(); // IMPORTANT: must call next() to continue
};

// Authentication middleware
const auth = (req, res, next) => {
  if (req.query.token === 'abc123') {
    next(); // Authenticated
  } else {
    res.status(401).send('Unauthorized');
  }
};

// Apply middleware globally (all routes)
app.use(logger);

// Apply middleware to specific route
app.get('/dashboard', auth, (req, res) => {
  res.send('Welcome to Dashboard');
});

app.get('/', (req, res) => {
  res.send('Home Page');
});

app.listen(3000, () => console.log('Server at localhost:3000'));

// Key Points:
// - next() MUST be called to proceed to the next middleware
// - Middleware executes in the order it is defined
// - app.use() applies middleware to ALL routes

